#### Society of Decorative Artists (1901–1945)

The rise of Art Deco coincided with an elevation in the status of decorative artists, who, until the late 19th century, were often relegated to the status of mere artisans. The term *arts décoratifs* was coined in 1875, granting official recognition to designers of furniture, textiles, and other decorative objects. In 1901, the *Société des artistes décorateurs* (Society of Decorative Artists), or SAD, was founded, ensuring that decorative artists held the same authorship rights as painters and sculptors. A similar movement unfolded in Italy, culminating in the 1902 *Esposizione Internazionale d'Arte Decorativa Moderna* ([International Exhibition of Modern Decorative Art](/Prima_Esposizione_Internazionale_d%27Arte_Decorativa_Moderna)) in [Turin](/Turin), the first international exhibition dedicated solely to decorative arts.

Several new magazines focused on decorative arts emerged in Paris, including *Arts et décoration* and *L'Art décoratif moderne*. Decorative arts sections were integrated into the annual salons of the *Société des artistes français* and later the [Salon d'Automne](/Salon_d%27Automne). French nationalism also played a role in this artistic resurgence, as French designers felt the competitive pressure from increasing exports of less expensive German furnishings. In 1911, the SAD proposed a significant international exposition of decorative arts for 1912, with the stipulation that only modern works, devoid of historical styles, would be permitted. The exhibition was postponed, first to 1914 and then to 1925, when it ultimately lent its name to the family of styles known as "Déco."

*   Table and chairs by [Maurice Dufrêne](/Maurice_Dufr%C3%AAne) and carpet by [Paul Follot](/Paul_Follot) at the 1912 [Salon des artistes décorateurs](/Soci%C3%A9t%C3%A9_des_artistes_d%C3%A9corateurs)
*   *Lady with Panther* by [George Barbier](/George_Barbier_(illustrator)) for [Louis Cartier](/Louis_Cartier) (1914). The display card commissioned by Cartier features a woman in a [Paul Poiret](/Paul_Poiret) gown.
*   Armchair by [Émile-Jacques Ruhlmann](/%C3%89mile-Jacques_Ruhlmann) (1914), now in the [Musée d'Orsay](/Mus%C3%A9e_d%27Orsay), Paris

Parisian department stores and prominent fashion designers were also key players in the ascent of Art Deco. Leading firms like the silverware manufacturer [Christofle](/Christofle), glass designer [René Lalique](/Ren%C3%A9_Lalique), and jewelers [Louis Cartier](/Louis_Cartier) and [Boucheron](/Boucheron) began to produce designs in more contemporary styles. From 1900 onwards, department stores actively recruited decorative artists for their in-house design studios. The decoration of the 1912 Salon d'Automne was entrusted to the department store [Printemps](/Printemps), which subsequently established its own workshop, Primavera, that same year. By 1920, Primavera employed over 300 artists whose styles ranged from updated interpretations of [Louis XIV](/Louis_XIV_style), [Louis XVI](/Louis_XVI_style), and particularly [Louis Philippe](/Louis_Philippe_style) furniture, conceived by Louis Süe and the Primavera workshop, to more avant-garde forms emerging from the studio of the Au Louvre department store. Other designers, such as [Émile-Jacques Ruhlmann](/%C3%89mile-Jacques_Ruhlmann) and Paul Follot, eschewed mass production, insisting on the unique creation of each piece. Early Art Deco was characterized by luxurious and exotic materials like [ebony](/Ebony), [ivory](/Ivory), and silk, vibrant color palettes, and stylized motifs, especially floral arrangements, which contributed to its distinctly modern aesthetic.

#### Salon d'Automne (1903–1914)

*   Main article: [Salon d'Automne](/Salon_d%27Automne)

*   Set for [Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov](/Nikolai_Rimsky-Korsakov)'s ballet [Sheherazade](/Scheherazade_(Rimsky-Korsakov)) by [Léon Bakst](/L%C3%A9on_Bakst) (1910)
*   Art Deco armchair made for art collector [Jacques Doucet](/Jacques_Doucet_(fashion_designer)) (1912–13)
*   Display of early Art Deco furnishings by the *Atelier français* at the 1912 [Salon d'Automne](/Salon_d%27Automne) from *Art et décoration* magazine (1914)

In its nascent stages, between 1910 and 1914, Art Deco manifested as a vibrant explosion of color, featuring bold and often contrasting hues, frequently rendered in floral designs. These were applied to furniture upholstery, carpets, screens, wallpaper, and fabrics. The 1912 [Salon des artistes décorateurs](/Soci%C3%A9t%C3%A9_des_artistes_d%C3%A9corateurs) showcased numerous colorful works, including chairs and a table by [Maurice Dufrêne](/Maurice_Dufr%C3%AAne) and a vivid Gobelin carpet by [Paul Follot](/Paul_Follot). In 1912–1913, designer [Adrien Karbowsky](/Adrien_Karbowsky) created a floral chair adorned with a parrot motif for the hunting lodge of art collector [Jacques Doucet](/Jacques_Doucet_(fashion_designer)). The furniture designers Louis Süe and [André Mare](/Andr%C3%A9_Mare) made their debut at the 1912 exhibition under the banner of the *Atelier français*, combining polychromatic fabrics with exotic and opulent materials such as ebony and ivory. Following World War I, they rose to prominence as one of the leading French interior design firms, responsible for the furnishings in the first-class salons and cabins of French transatlantic [ocean liners](/Ocean_liner).

The vivid colorations of Art Deco drew inspiration from various sources. The exotic stage designs by [Léon Bakst](/L%C3%A9on_Bakst) for the [Ballets Russes](/Ballets_Russes) created a sensation in Paris just before World War I. Some of the color choices were influenced by the earlier [Fauvism](/Fauvism) movement, led by [Henri Matisse](/Henri_Matisse), while others were inspired by the [Orphism](/Orphism_(art)) of painters like [Sonia Delaunay](/Sonia_Delaunay). Additionally, the movement known as [Les Nabis](/Les_Nabis) and the symbolic painter Odilon Redon, who designed fireplace screens and other decorative items, contributed to the palette. Bright shades were a hallmark of fashion designer [Paul Poiret](/Paul_Poiret)'s work, significantly influencing both Art Deco fashion and interior design.

#### Théâtre des Champs-Élysées (1910–1913)

*   [Théâtre des Champs-Élysées](/Th%C3%A9%C3%A2tre_des_Champs-%C3%89lys%C3%A9es) by [Auguste Perret](/Auguste_Perret) at 15, avenue Montaigne, Paris (1910–1913). Reinforced concrete allowed architects to create new forms and larger spaces.
*   *La Danse*, a [bas-relief](/Relief) on the façade of the Théâtre des Champs-Élysées by [Antoine Bourdelle](/Antoine_Bourdelle) (1912)
*   Interior of the Théâtre des Champs-Élysées, with Bourdelle's bas-reliefs above the stage
*   Dome of the Theater, with an Art Deco rose design by [Maurice Denis](/Maurice_Denis)

*Apollon et sa méditation entourée des 9 muses* (Apollo and His Meditation Surrounded by the 9 Muses), a bas-relief on the façade of the Théâtre des Champs-Élysées by Bourdelle (1910–1912). This work is considered one of the earliest examples of what would become known as Art Deco sculpture.

The [Théâtre des Champs-Élysées](/Th%C3%A9%C3%A2tre_des_Champs-%C3%89lys%C3%A9es) (1910–1913), designed by [Auguste Perret](/Auguste_Perret), stands as the first landmark Art Deco building completed in Paris. Prior to this, [reinforced concrete](/Reinforced_concrete) had primarily been used for industrial and apartment buildings. Perret had previously constructed the first modern reinforced-concrete apartment building in Paris at rue Benjamin Franklin in 1903–04. [Henri Sauvage](/Henri_Sauvage), another significant future Art Deco architect, built another apartment building at 7, rue Trétaigne in 1904.

From 1908 to 1910, a 21-year-old Le Corbusier worked as a draftsman in Perret's office, absorbing the techniques of concrete construction. Perret's building exhibited a clean, rectangular form and geometric ornamentation, characteristics that would become hallmarks of Art Deco. The theatre's décor was equally groundbreaking; the [façade](/Fa%C3%A7ade) was adorned with [high reliefs](/High-relief) by [Antoine Bourdelle](/Antoine_Bourdelle), a dome by [Maurice Denis](/Maurice_Denis), paintings by [Édouard Vuillard](/%C3%89douard_Vuillard), and an Art Deco curtain by [Ker-Xavier Roussel](/Ker-Xavier_Roussel). The theatre quickly became a premier venue for the early performances of the [Ballets Russes](/Ballets_Russes). Perret and Sauvage went on to become the leading Art Deco architects in Paris during the 1920s.

#### Cubism

*   Design for the façade of [La Maison Cubiste](/La_Maison_Cubiste) (Cubist House) by [Raymond Duchamp-Villon](/Raymond_Duchamp-Villon) (1912)
*   Detail of the entrance of *La Maison Cubiste* at the 1912 Salon d'Automne
*   *Le Salon Bourgeois*, designed by [André Mare](/Andr%C3%A9_Mare) inside *La Maison Cubiste*, in the decorative arts section of the 1912 Salon d'Automne. Metzinger's [Femme à l'Éventail](/Femme_%C3%A0_l%27%C3%89ventail) can be seen hanging on the left wall.
*   Cubist villa at 3-49 Libušina Street, [Vyšehrad](/%C5%A0ehrad) (Prague), by [Josef Chochol](/Josef_Chochol) (1912–13). Chochol was one of three Czech architects (members of the [Mánes Union of Fine Arts](/M%C3%A1nes_Union_of_Fine_Arts)), along with [Pavel Janák](/Pavel_Jan%C3%A1k) and [Josef Gočár](/Josef_Go%C4%8D%C3%A1r), who were influenced by Cubism.

*Danseuse (Femme à l'éventail, Femme à la cruche)* by [Joseph Csaky](/Joseph_Csaky) (1912), original plaster, exhibited at the 1912 [Salon d'Automne](/Salon_d%27Automne) and the 1914 [Salon des Indépendants], a proto-Art Deco sculpture.

The [art movement](/Art_movement) known as [Cubism](/Cubism), which emerged in France between 1907 and 1912, significantly influenced the development of Art Deco. In *Art Deco Complete: The Definitive Guide to the Decorative Arts of the 1920s and 1930s*, Alastair Duncan observes, "Cubism, in some bastardized form or other, became the lingua franca of the era's decorative artists." The Cubists, themselves influenced by [Paul Cézanne](/Paul_C%C3%A9zanne), focused on simplifying forms to their fundamental geometric shapes: the cylinder, the sphere, and the cone.

In 1912, artists associated with the [Section d'Or](/Section_d%27Or) exhibited works that were considerably more accessible to the general public than the analytical Cubism pioneered by Picasso and Braque. The Cubist vocabulary proved particularly appealing to fashion, furniture, and interior designers.

The Art *Décoratif* section of the 1912 Salon d'Automne featured an architectural installation known as [La Maison Cubiste](/La_Maison_Cubiste). The façade was designed by [Raymond Duchamp-Villon](/Raymond_Duchamp-Villon), while the interior décor was by [André Mare](/Andr%C3%A9_Mare). *La Maison Cubiste* was a fully furnished installation, complete with a façade, staircase, wrought-iron banisters, a bedroom, and a living room—the *Salon Bourgeois*. Paintings by [Albert Gleizes](/Albert_Gleizes), [Jean Metzinger](/Jean_Metzinger), [Marie Laurencin](/Marie_Laurencin), [Marcel Duchamp](/Marcel_Duchamp), [Fernand Léger](/Fernand_L%C3%A9ger), and [Roger de La Fresnaye](/Roger_de_La_Fresnaye) were displayed within. Thousands of visitors to the salon passed through this full-scale model.

The house's façade, designed by Duchamp-Villon, was not radically avant-garde by contemporary standards; it featured prismatic shapes on the lintels and pediments but otherwise resembled a conventional house of the period. For the interior spaces, Mare designed wallpaper adorned with stylized roses and floral patterns, along with complementary upholstery, furniture, and carpets, all featuring flamboyant and colorful motifs—a distinct departure from traditional décor. Critic Emile Sedeyn noted in *Art et Décoration* magazine: "He does not embarrass himself with simplicity, for he multiplies flowers wherever they can be put. The effect he seeks is obviously one of picturesqueness and gaiety. He achieves it." The Cubist element was primarily conveyed through the artwork. The installation faced criticism for its perceived radicalism, which paradoxically contributed to its success. This architectural installation was subsequently exhibited at the 1913 [Armory Show](/Armory_Show) in New York City, as well as in Chicago and Boston. Largely due to this exhibition, the term "Cubist" began to be applied to anything modern, from hairstyles to clothing to theatrical performances.

The influence of Cubism persisted within Art Deco, even as the latter style branched out in numerous other directions. As Richard Harrison Martin of the Metropolitan Museum of Art observed, "Cubism's adumbrated geometry became coin of the realm in the 1920s. Art Deco's development of Cubism's selective geometry into a wider array of shapes carried Cubism as a pictorial taxonomy to a much broader audience and wider appeal."

### Influences

#### Pre-World War I European styles

*   [Ballets Russes](/Ballets_Russes) influences – Drawing of the dancer [Vaslav Nijinsky](/Vaslav_Nijinsky), by Paris fashion artist [Georges Barbier](/Georges_Barbier) (1913)
*   [Rococo](/Rococo) – Chest of drawers, by [Jacques Dubois](/Jacques_Dubois) (1750–1755), various wood types and gilt bronze mounts, [Waddesdon Manor](/Waddesdon_Manor), Buckinghamshire, UK
*   Rococo influences – Commode, by Paul Iribarne Garay (c. 1912), mahogany and tulip wood frame, slate top, green-tinted shagreen upholstery, ebony knobs, base and garlands, [Museum of Decorative Arts](/Mus%C3%A9e_des_Arts_d%C3%A9coratifs,_Paris), Paris
*   [Beaux-Arts architecture](/Beaux_Arts_architecture) – Boulevard Diderot no. 21, Paris, unknown architect (c. 1910)
*   Beaux Arts influences – Avenue de Versailles no. 70–72, Paris, "Modern" decor in an established typology, designed by Paul Delaplace and sculpted by [Jean Boucher](/Jean_Boucher_(artist)) (1928)
*   [Louis XVI style](/Louis_XVI_style) – Corner table, by [Jean-François Chalgrin](/Jean-Fran%C3%A7ois_Chalgrin) (1770), gilded wood, [Corcoran Gallery of Art](/Corcoran_Gallery_of_Art), Washington, D.C.
*   Louis XVI style influences – Dressing table and chair set, by [Paul Follot](/Paul_Follot) (1919), marble and wood encrusted, lacquered and gilded, [Musée d'Art Moderne de Paris](/Mus%C3%A9e_d%27Art_Moderne_de_Paris)
*   [Neoclassicism](/Neoclassicism) – *Mercury or The Trade*, by [Augustin Pajou](/Augustin_Pajou) (1780), marble, [Louvre](/Louvre), Paris
*   Neoclassical influences – *Prometheus* ([Manship](/Paul_Manship)), a stylized Art Deco update of classical sculpture, by [Paul Manship](/Paul_Manship) (1936), gilded bronze, [Rockefeller Center](/Rockefeller_Center), New York City
*   [Art Nouveau](/Art_Nouveau) – [Hôtel Guimard](/H%C3%B4tel_Guimard_(Art_Nouveau)) (Avenue Mozart no. 122), Paris, by [Hector Guimard](/Hector_Guimard) (1909)
*   Art Nouveau influences – Sinuous curves on the façade of [Avenue Montaigne](/Avenue_Montaigne) no. 26, Paris, by Louis Duhayon and Marcel Julien (1937)

In its decorative aspects, Art Deco absorbed influences from a wide array of sources. It represented a departure from, and often a reaction against, [Art Nouveau](/Art_Nouveau), a style that had flourished in Europe between 1895 and 1900. Art Deco coexisted with and drew from [Beaux-Arts](/Beaux-Arts_architecture) and [neoclassical](/Neoclassical_architecture) styles prevalent in European and American architecture. In 1905, [Eugène Grasset](/Eug%C3%A8ne_Grasset) published *Méthode de Composition Ornementale, Éléments Rectilignes*, a systematic exploration of the decorative potential of geometric elements, forms, and motifs. This work stood in contrast to the undulating, organic style of [Hector Guimard](/Hector_Guimard), which had been highly popular in Paris. Grasset championed the principle that fundamental geometric shapes, such as triangles and squares, formed the basis of all compositional arrangements. The reinforced-concrete structures of Auguste Perret and Henri Sauvage, particularly the [Théâtre des Champs-Élysées](/Th%C3%A9%C3%A2tre_des_Champs-%C3%89lys%C3%A9es), introduced a novel approach to construction and decoration that was emulated globally.

#### Ancient and non-European civilizations

*   [Ancient Egyptian art](/Ancient_Egyptian_art) – Vegetal [capitals](/Capital_(architecture)) in the courtyard of the Isis Temple, [Philae](/Philae_temple_complex), Egypt, unknown architect (380 BC–117 AD)
*   Egyptian influences – Dress with lotus flowers inspired by Ancient Egyptian decoration, by Jenny (couturier) and Lesage (embroiderer) (1925), silk, metallic thread, and crocheted embroidery, [Musée Galliera](/Mus%C3%A9e_Galliera), Paris
*   [Mesopotamian art](/Mesopotamian_art) – [Ziggurat of Ur](/Ziggurat_of_Ur) in [Tell el-Muqayyar](/Tell_el-Muqayyar), Dhi Qar Province, Iraq, unknown architect (21st century BC)
*   Mesopotamian influences – [Western Union Building](/60_Hudson_Street) (Hudson Street no. 60) in New York City, by [Voorhees, Gmelin and Walker](/Voorhees,_Gmelin_and_Walker) (1928–1930)
*   [Pre-Columbian art](/Pre-Columbian_art) (in this case [Maya](/Ancient_Maya_art)) – [Yaxchilan Lintel 24](/Yaxchilan_Lintel_24) (702 AD), limestone, [British Museum](/British_Museum), London
*   Pre-Columbian influences (in this case Maya) – Interior detail of [450 Sutter Street](/450_Sutter_Street) in [San Francisco](/San_Francisco), California, by [Timothy L. Pflueger](/Timothy_L._Pflueger) (1929)
*   Sub-Saharan [African](/African_art) (in this case produced in the [Kuba Kingdom](/Kuba_Kingdom) from present-day [Democratic Republic of the Congo](/Democratic_Republic_of_the_Congo)) – [Ndop](/Ndop_(Kuba)) of King Mishe miShyaang maMbul (1760–1780), wood, [Brooklyn Museum](/Brooklyn_Museum), New York City
*   Sub-Saharan African influences – *Winter 1930*, by [Léon Benigni](/L%C3%A9on_Benigni), oil on canvas, private collection

Art Deco designers drew inspiration from a wide range of global sources, often found in museums like the [Musée du Louvre](/Mus%C3%A9e_du_Louvre), [Musée de l'Homme](/Mus%C3%A9e_de_l%27Homme), and the [Musée national des Arts d'Afrique et d'Océanie](/Mus%C3%A9e_national_des_Arts_d%27Afrique_et_d%27Oc%C3%A9anie). The popular fascination with archaeology, fueled by excavations at [Pompeii](/Pompeii), [Troy](/Troy), and the tomb of Pharaoh [Tutankhamun](/Tutankhamun), also contributed significantly. Artists and designers integrated motifs from [ancient Egypt](/Ancient_Egypt), [Africa](/Africa), [Mesopotamia](/Mesopotamia), [Greece](/Ancient_Greece), [Rome](/Ancient_Rome), Asia, [Mesoamerica](/Mesoamerica), and Oceania, blending them with elements of the [Machine Age](/Machine_Age).

#### Early 20th-century avant-garde movements

*   [Primitivism](/Primitivism) – *Head of a Woman*, by [Amedeo Modigliani](/Amedeo_Modigliani) (1910–11), limestone, [National Gallery of Art](/National_Gallery_of_Art), Washington, D.C.
*   Primitivist influences – Bust for a shop window, anonymous Belgian artist (c. 1920), painted [papier-mâché](/Papier-m%C3%A2ch%C3%A9), private collection, [Cologne](/Cologne), Germany
*   [De Stijl](/De_Stijl) – [Rietveld Schröder House](/Rietveld_Schr%C3%B6der_House) in [Utrecht](/Utrecht), Netherlands, by [Gerrit Rietveld](/Gerrit_Rietveld) (1924)
*   De Stijl influences – Pavillon du Tourisme, by [Robert Mallet-Stevens](/Robert_Mallet-Stevens), [International Exhibition of Modern Decorative and Industrial Arts](/International_Exhibition_of_Modern_Decorative_and_Industrial_Arts), Paris (1925)
